{"ts": "2026-06-07T20:29:50.574852+00:00", "update": {"tools": {"messages": [{"type": "tool", "data": {"content": [{"type": "text", "text": "successfully downloaded text file (SHA: 761394d4c1bc093dffd57dd9d470512c6d645aaf)", "id": "lc_849424e3-b58b-499e-bc74-e18224835aee"}, {"type": "text", "text": "# Default profile set shipped with vidpack.\n# Edit to customize or add profiles. Profile names must be lowercase ASCII.\n\n[web]\ncontainer = \"mp4\"\nvideo_codec = \"libx264\"\naudio_codec = \"aac\"\nvideo_bitrate = \"2M\"\nscale = \"1280:720\"\n\n[archive]\ncontainer = \"mkv\"\nvideo_codec = \"libx265\"\naudio_codec = \"flac\"\ncrf = 18\nscale = \"source\"\n\n[gif]\ncontainer = \"gif\"\nfps = 12\nscale = \"480:-1\"\n# Note: the gif profile currently uses a single-pass palette generation,\n# which is convenient but produces noticeably worse quality than a proper\n# two-pass palettegen / paletteuse pipeline. Known limitation; tracked in\n# the issue tracker.\n", "id": "lc_63179701-97ee-4696-b819-76956dc53ed5"}], "additional_kwargs": {}, "response_metadata": {}, "type": "tool", "name": "get_file_contents", "id": "4f880c92-5e59-46c5-931f-29be5137296d", "tool_call_id": "call_ac40f6387bf949f1b580e984", "artifact": null, "status": "success"}}]}}}
{"ts": "2026-06-07T20:29:50.592643+00:00", "update": {"tools": {"messages": [{"type": "tool", "data": {"content": [{"type": "text", "text": "successfully downloaded text file (SHA: dd8f230ebcee1ed2c87953be052ec8d2681c21fc)", "id": "lc_ffa3f1d7-03d7-4095-9fe8-db64e8d728c9"}, {"type": "text", "text": "# vidpack — profile-driven FFmpeg wrapper\n\n`vidpack` is a small Python CLI that runs FFmpeg using named profiles defined\nin `profiles.toml`. The goal is to avoid memorizing long ffmpeg flag strings\nfor routine encoding jobs.\n\nFFmpeg is **not** bundled. `vidpack` expects `ffmpeg` (and `ffprobe`, where\nrelevant) to be available on `PATH`.\n\n## Install\n\n```\npip install -e .\n```\n\nThis registers the `vidpack` command.\n\n## Profiles\n\nThe default `profiles.toml` ships three profiles:\n\n| Profile   | Container | Video codec | Audio codec | Notes                       |\n|-----------|-----------|-------------|-------------|-----------------------------|\n| `web`     | mp4       | libx264     | aac         | 720p, target bitrate 2 Mbps |\n| `archive` | mkv       | libx265     | flac        | source resolution, CRF 18   |\n| `gif`     | gif       | (palette)   | (none)      | 480p wide, 12 fps           |\n\nEdit `profiles.toml` to customize or add profiles.\n\n## Usage\n\n```\nvidpack <profile> <input> [-o OUTPUT] [--dry-run]\n```\n\nIf `-o` is omitted, the output filename is derived from the input by\nreplacing the extension with the profile's container extension.\n\n`--dry-run` prints the ffmpeg command vidpack would run, without executing it.\n\nBy default, vidpack will **not** overwrite an existing output file; it exits\nwith an error. Delete the output manually or pass a different `-o`.\n\n## Examples\n\n```\n# Re-encode an mp4 for web at 720p\nvidpack web input.mov -o talk.mp4\n\n# Lossless-ish archive copy\nvidpack archive input.mov\n\n# Preview the ffmpeg command for the gif profile without running it\nvidpack gif clip.mp4 --dry-run\n```\n\n## License\n\nMIT\n", "id": "lc_e500d36d-005a-4ad3-97d7-dbc7f999b60b"}], "additional_kwargs": {}, "response_metadata": {}, "type": "tool", "name": "get_file_contents", "id": "d15b4337-6081-49e9-a9e4-f899821590c6", "tool_call_id": "call_da6eb5cb04d9402ea0c7afad", "artifact": null, "status": "success"}}]}}}
